    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1892-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1892-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="308"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d308">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Smith</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1892-02-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 25, 1892</hi>
                        </date>. (Received March 12.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 151.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your telegram of the 18th instant, advising me that the steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Indiana</hi>, laden with flour for Russia, given by the
                    citizens of Philadelphia, would sail on the 22d, and instructing me to see that
                    the American consul or some other fit man should coöperate with the agent who
                    goes to take care of and distribute the gift. On this instruction I replied by
                    telegraph on the <pb facs="0458" n="370" xml:id="pg_370"/> 20th as follows:
                    “Steamship <hi rend="italic">Indiana</hi> will be received on arrival by
                    American consul-general and others. Full arrangements will be made for prompt
                    distribution of cargo as donors may determine. Desirable to know in advance
                    amount in tons. Can assure faithful, conscientious distribution of all American
                    gifts as givers may wish.”</p>
                <p>Subsequent dispatches will indicate the arrangements more in detail.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Chas. Emory Smith.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
